WEBVTT

00:58.100 --> 01:01.103
-(birds calling)
-(insects trilling)

01:07.234 --> 01:09.153
HARRY TURNER (whispering):
It's a squirrel.

01:11.822 --> 01:13.824
That squirrel's gonna go...

01:13.908 --> 01:15.659
Get it. Get it.

01:16.827 --> 01:18.829
Get it.

01:18.913 --> 01:20.623
It's a squirrel.

01:22.625 --> 01:24.668
Go. Go.

01:27.379 --> 01:29.381
♪ ♪

01:48.901 --> 01:50.902
(growling softly)

02:03.332 --> 02:04.959
(panting)

02:18.722 --> 02:20.599
(sniffing)

02:23.185 --> 02:25.187
♪ ♪

02:27.314 --> 02:28.899
(growls softly)

02:30.609 --> 02:32.611
(growling)

02:35.281 --> 02:37.199
(growling softly)

02:37.283 --> 02:39.285
Don't play with it.

02:39.368 --> 02:41.579
I'm gonna get it. I'm gonna get it.

02:41.662 --> 02:43.664
(growling)

02:47.042 --> 02:48.210
Eat it.

02:48.293 --> 02:50.296
(growls viciously)

02:55.801 --> 02:58.512
We're wild animals, me and you.

02:58.596 --> 02:59.972
We're wild.

03:00.055 --> 03:01.807
(growling)

03:14.194 --> 03:16.530
-(tapping)
-Come here.

03:16.614 --> 03:18.616
Come here.

03:27.583 --> 03:29.835
(groaning)

03:29.919 --> 03:32.880
(chuckling)

03:32.963 --> 03:34.924
Okay, piggyback.

03:36.508 --> 03:38.886
The reintroduction was always
for one reason.

03:38.969 --> 03:42.180
That was to put a wildcat
back into the wild again.

03:42.264 --> 03:44.016
But it's just hard.

03:45.100 --> 03:48.145
It's hard to let go of something you love.

03:48.228 --> 03:50.272
Especially when you're
letting him go into, like,

03:50.356 --> 03:52.816
one of the most dangerous environments
in the world.

03:52.900 --> 03:54.526
(bird calls in distance)

03:57.696 --> 03:59.698
♪ ♪

04:01.909 --> 04:04.703
(faint, distorted gunfire)

04:04.787 --> 04:06.372
(shotgun fires)

04:06.455 --> 04:08.040
(heavy gunfire)

04:12.169 --> 04:13.504
(yelling)

04:14.755 --> 04:16.923
REPORTER:
Private Harry Turner is just 18,

04:17.007 --> 04:19.218
one of the youngest soldiers here.

04:19.301 --> 04:23.055
He only finished training in March
and is now on a six-month tour.

04:23.138 --> 04:24.765
HARRY:
My mum was a little bit, like,

04:24.848 --> 04:27.267
shocked because she thought
I was only going to be out here

04:27.351 --> 04:31.105
for two weeks, but nah, my mum, dad,
they're all supportive about it.

04:31.188 --> 04:32.982
(heavy gunfire)

04:33.065 --> 04:35.442
(indistinct shouting)

04:49.373 --> 04:51.457
I was medically discharged

04:51.542 --> 04:55.462
with recurrent depression and PTSD.

04:58.257 --> 05:02.636
After Afghanistan, I struggled so badly.

05:02.720 --> 05:06.306
I felt that life wasn't worth living

05:06.390 --> 05:09.226
and maybe I should just pack up
all of my things

05:09.309 --> 05:11.311
and just go where no one knows where I am,

05:11.395 --> 05:14.064
no one knows if I'm alive,
no one knows if I'm dead.

05:21.905 --> 05:24.491
(quiet chatter)

05:24.575 --> 05:26.285
(child coughing)

05:27.369 --> 05:29.371
And then when I met Sam,

05:29.455 --> 05:32.791
that's when my life really took a turn.

05:32.875 --> 05:35.836
(indistinct chatter)

05:35.919 --> 05:37.838
SAMANTHA ZWICKER:
You know, when I came across Harry,

05:37.921 --> 05:39.423
he was extremely misunderstood.

05:39.506 --> 05:43.510
This, you know, boy who went to war
instead of going to college,

05:43.594 --> 05:46.513
which is what a lot of people see
when they look at him.

05:47.598 --> 05:50.683
But I obviously saw something
super special in him.

05:50.768 --> 05:52.770
He spent his time in the jungle

05:52.853 --> 05:56.065
volunteering and helping me
with, like, this greater cause.

05:56.148 --> 05:59.693
Just carrying a sloth on my back
through the jungle.

05:59.777 --> 06:04.615
Gonna get him back, give him some food,
put him back up a tree.

06:08.243 --> 06:12.748
Sam could've easily stayed at home
and just studied at university.

06:12.831 --> 06:14.750
You know, the usual.

06:15.751 --> 06:19.004
But she was out there in the jungle,
physically doing it.

06:29.640 --> 06:33.435
SAMANTHA: I started Hoja Nueva
after I first came to Peru.

06:33.519 --> 06:35.020
(birds screeching)

06:35.104 --> 06:37.231
I came as a student
to do wildlife research.

06:37.314 --> 06:39.149
Yeah, look how big these are.

06:39.233 --> 06:41.026
Huge ocelot.

06:41.110 --> 06:42.236
Poop, poop, poop, poop.

06:42.319 --> 06:45.072
And I stayed because I saw a need

06:45.155 --> 06:48.742
not just for research but for being a part
of the conservation efforts as a whole.

06:48.826 --> 06:52.746
I'm saying I'm going to pay five dollars
per sample collected of cat scat.

06:52.830 --> 06:54.665
Now, that is how you motivate people.

06:54.748 --> 06:57.292
Right? Am I right? (laughs)

06:57.376 --> 06:59.002
(speaking Spanish)

06:59.086 --> 07:03.382
And it's just morphed
and-and grown a lot since then.

07:03.465 --> 07:06.051
NIERY:
We as an NGO

07:06.135 --> 07:10.305
try very hard to prevent deforestation
and hunting.

07:10.389 --> 07:13.600
SAMANTHA: It's a Peruvian nonprofit,
and it's a place that

07:13.684 --> 07:16.270
animals that don't have another chance
can come to.

07:18.188 --> 07:19.398
SAMANTHA:
Hi!

07:20.941 --> 07:21.942
Hi! Hi!

07:24.153 --> 07:27.322
Hi, I'm Samantha. I'm good, you?

07:27.698 --> 07:28.782
Nice to meet you.

07:28.866 --> 07:32.536
You have a family of animals.
I like it a lot.

07:33.704 --> 07:36.331
It's like my family. (laughing)

07:36.415 --> 07:41.670
I think it will take time
to be wild again,

07:41.753 --> 07:44.464
but little by little he can.

07:45.507 --> 07:47.092
Let's see.

07:47.176 --> 07:48.719
Banana. (gasps)

07:53.432 --> 07:55.308
Yeah? Okay.

07:56.518 --> 07:58.020
-(mutters) It's okay.
-(squeals)

08:06.111 --> 08:09.781
SAMANTHA: We get animals
because of things like logging, mining,

08:09.865 --> 08:12.993
wildlife trafficking,
people selling animals in markets.

08:13.076 --> 08:18.332
And we have to do what we can
to get the younger animals rehabilitated.

08:18.415 --> 08:20.459
(speaking Spanish)

08:21.919 --> 08:24.296
Their alternative is living
in a cement box

08:24.379 --> 08:27.049
or getting euthanized

08:27.132 --> 08:29.384
or dying in a much worse way.

08:30.469 --> 08:32.346
Billy!

08:33.429 --> 08:37.934
They live, basically, in larger herds
on the other side of the river from us,

08:38.018 --> 08:39.645
but we're still gonna try
to reintroduce him

08:39.727 --> 08:41.355
because pigs are quite easy in that way.

08:43.565 --> 08:46.360
He never had a mama. You can tell.

08:46.443 --> 08:48.946
You can always tell
when they've never had a mama.

08:56.161 --> 08:58.163
He's a baby.

09:00.332 --> 09:02.042
Baby paca-rana.

09:03.293 --> 09:04.670
What are you doing?

09:06.004 --> 09:07.256
What are you doing?

09:07.339 --> 09:09.299
SAMANTHA:
It's hard to describe, like,

09:09.383 --> 09:12.427
the feeling of being in a place
that still has beauty like this.

09:12.511 --> 09:14.054
-(laughing)
-(muttering)

09:14.137 --> 09:17.641
Being around animals, being around nature,

09:17.724 --> 09:20.143
not having that many people around.

09:21.144 --> 09:22.437
Harry, what you looking at?

09:22.521 --> 09:24.398
-Oh, you got a leaf in your hair.
-Oh.

09:24.481 --> 09:26.400
SAMANTHA:
Oh, my God! (laughs)

09:26.483 --> 09:29.069
I've seen the jungle here change people.

09:29.152 --> 09:31.571
♪ ♪

09:31.655 --> 09:33.657
(laughs)

09:37.744 --> 09:39.830
(laughter)

09:43.750 --> 09:45.502
Whoa!

09:49.172 --> 09:52.634
(laughter)

09:53.719 --> 09:55.554
(laughing):
Harry, no.

09:55.637 --> 09:57.806
-(squeals) Oh, my God!
-(laughter)

10:00.475 --> 10:02.686
Three, two, one.

10:04.229 --> 10:06.356
(whoops, laughs)

10:10.944 --> 10:12.946
♪ ♪

10:16.450 --> 10:20.287
HARRY:
We became, you know, a team,

10:20.370 --> 10:22.622
best friends and partners,

10:22.706 --> 10:27.085
and when Khan came into our hands,

10:27.169 --> 10:30.464
that's when my life really had a purpose.

10:34.968 --> 10:37.929
Yesterday we rescued him

10:38.013 --> 10:41.224
from some illegal loggers.

10:41.308 --> 10:44.478
He was in a tree that they cut down.

10:44.561 --> 10:46.772
We've named him Khan.

10:46.855 --> 10:51.401
We're gonna try and do
a reintroduction program with him.

10:53.904 --> 10:56.865
It was an incredible feeling to know

10:56.948 --> 11:00.285
that this animal wasn't gonna be
going onto the black market,

11:00.369 --> 11:02.329
to know that its claws
weren't gonna be clipped

11:02.412 --> 11:04.873
or its teeth weren't gonna be ground down.

11:05.957 --> 11:07.667
No more biting of the face.

11:07.751 --> 11:10.545
(groaning)

11:17.552 --> 11:20.138
SAMANTHA:
Good baby. Good baby!

11:21.973 --> 11:23.517
HARRY:
Khan. (clicking tongue)

11:23.600 --> 11:26.311
-SAMANTHA: You want to go to Daddy?
-HARRY: Khan. (clicking tongue)

11:27.604 --> 11:29.022
(Samantha laughing)

11:29.106 --> 11:30.732
-HARRY: Good boy.
-SAMANTHA: You got it.

11:30.816 --> 11:32.526
(growls playfully)

11:32.609 --> 11:34.152
(Khan growls softly)

11:37.072 --> 11:40.951
SAMANTHA: The goal was always
that Khan would be a wild ocelot.

11:41.034 --> 11:43.537
That it was better
than living a life in the zoo.

11:43.620 --> 11:45.247
HARRY:
Good boy.

11:45.330 --> 11:47.290
SAMANTHA:
I started doing all the research possible

11:47.374 --> 11:50.043
to come up with a reintroduction plan.

11:51.962 --> 11:53.338
(growls)

11:53.422 --> 11:56.383
HARRY:
Come join Mummy up in the tree.

11:56.466 --> 11:58.802
Good boy.

11:58.885 --> 12:00.720
SAMANTHA:
The biggest kind of challenge was

12:00.804 --> 12:02.681
no one had done it before.

12:02.764 --> 12:05.725
They've never actively spent time
with a wildcat for a year,

12:05.809 --> 12:08.270
a year and a half, two years,
and then reintroduced it.

12:08.353 --> 12:10.230
It's just never been done.

12:10.313 --> 12:12.524
Mosquitoes are bad tonight,
as you can tell.

12:12.607 --> 12:15.861
But I just found this little dude.

12:15.944 --> 12:17.404
Khan.

12:17.487 --> 12:19.322
He's here. (hisses playfully)

12:21.366 --> 12:23.160
(rodent squeaking)

12:24.161 --> 12:25.454
Where is it?

12:25.537 --> 12:27.080
Did you lose it?

12:27.164 --> 12:30.208
Right, when you get something,
you have to kill it.

12:30.292 --> 12:32.085
You have to.

12:32.169 --> 12:34.087
Otherwise, you're gonna die out here.

12:35.672 --> 12:38.258
I didn't know if it was gonna be doable,

12:38.341 --> 12:41.761
but Sam had a lot of faith in me.

12:41.845 --> 12:44.639
SAMANTHA: I don't think there's anyone
that's better-suited for this project.

12:44.723 --> 12:46.975
It doesn't matter if you come
from an academic background

12:47.058 --> 12:49.144
or you have a master's or a PhD.

12:49.227 --> 12:51.646
Most people couldn't survive here.

12:51.730 --> 12:53.607
A lot of people come down
and do research projects

12:53.690 --> 12:57.402
that last three months
and can't even usually last that long,

12:57.486 --> 13:00.947
living day-to-day
in the Amazon rain forest.

13:01.031 --> 13:06.578
So, Harry's history and experience
with being in harsh environments,

13:06.661 --> 13:08.914
it makes him suited for this project.

13:11.875 --> 13:13.627
He can smell something.

13:13.710 --> 13:15.337
(Khan growls)

13:19.257 --> 13:25.055
I'm gonna have to teach Khan
that this caiman here can be food.

13:25.138 --> 13:26.932
It's moving.

13:30.101 --> 13:31.520
Okay.

13:31.603 --> 13:34.439
Khan got bitten by him,
so now he's a bit scared of...

13:34.523 --> 13:36.191
He doesn't know what to do.

13:36.274 --> 13:39.110
Khan, you've got to grab the neck.

13:39.194 --> 13:41.154
I've got him.

13:41.238 --> 13:42.906
Good boy.

13:46.076 --> 13:49.120
Good boy. Good boy.

13:51.456 --> 13:54.709
I'd like to say a huge thank-you
for the amount of support that we've had

13:54.793 --> 13:57.629
through the Khan ReWilding project.

13:57.712 --> 14:00.715
Um, we would not be able to do this
without you at all,

14:00.799 --> 14:05.262
and he is growing up very, very quickly.

14:05.345 --> 14:08.515
He's getting very, very boisterous.

14:08.598 --> 14:11.268
And soon,

14:11.351 --> 14:14.813
hopefully, he'll be off
in the wild by himself.

14:14.896 --> 14:16.856
(growling softly)

14:19.693 --> 14:23.029
Look how fat this little bugger is.

14:23.113 --> 14:24.864
Look at your belly!

14:26.199 --> 14:29.828
(laughing)

14:29.911 --> 14:33.707
It really just makes me think,
"You're okay, you know?

14:33.790 --> 14:38.295
"This... this world that you live in is...

14:38.378 --> 14:40.380
isn't so bad after all."

14:40.463 --> 14:42.465
(growling playfully)

14:44.009 --> 14:47.846
He's saving me, and I'm saving him.

14:47.929 --> 14:49.598
-Good boy.
-SAMANTHA: Khan.

14:50.682 --> 14:52.976
(Samantha growling playfully)

14:56.771 --> 14:57.981
Okay.

14:58.064 --> 14:59.608
Ow! That's my ear.

15:00.609 --> 15:03.445
These claws there...

15:03.528 --> 15:05.530
fucking size of them go into you.

15:13.330 --> 15:15.749
Ow. Fucking hell.

15:17.167 --> 15:19.836
He clawed me straight in the fucking face.

15:20.920 --> 15:23.131
Ah, ah, ah, ah, ah! The ear.

15:23.214 --> 15:24.966
Ah, shit.

15:25.050 --> 15:27.344
I'm recording this so that...

15:28.428 --> 15:29.929
No, that's my hat.

15:30.013 --> 15:33.058
Because, when I miss you,

15:33.141 --> 15:35.644
when I'm back in England,

15:35.727 --> 15:40.940
I can look back on this video
and think what a little shit he was.

15:41.983 --> 15:43.985
(insects trilling)

15:48.281 --> 15:49.824
Khan, where are you?

15:51.117 --> 15:52.952
-(gunshot)
-Shit!

15:55.538 --> 15:58.249
(grunting)

15:58.333 --> 16:01.002
(Khan growling)

16:02.796 --> 16:05.423
Hi. Hi.

16:05.507 --> 16:07.133
You're okay.

16:07.217 --> 16:08.718
Come here.

16:17.018 --> 16:19.729
(crying):
My poor boy.

16:19.813 --> 16:22.649
My poor boy is so fucked.

16:23.817 --> 16:26.361
His fucking front paw's hanging off.

16:28.530 --> 16:30.949
(sniffles) It's okay, boy.

16:31.032 --> 16:32.826
(growls)

16:32.909 --> 16:34.994
The vets are on their way.

16:36.871 --> 16:39.415
I was walking with Khan.

16:39.499 --> 16:44.212
There was a gun which has a bit of string
that triggers it

16:44.295 --> 16:46.923
when something walks in front of it

16:47.006 --> 16:49.342
that hunters put out.

16:49.426 --> 16:52.262
Shot him in the front leg.

16:52.345 --> 16:54.514
I'm trying to keep positive,

16:54.597 --> 16:58.017
but I'm so fucking angry and sad
at the same time.

17:01.271 --> 17:03.273
And in my head, I keep thinking,

17:03.356 --> 17:06.151
"Right, he's gonna be okay,
he's gonna be okay."

17:08.236 --> 17:10.696
(sobs)

17:10.780 --> 17:12.781
I don't know what to do.

17:12.866 --> 17:14.867
♪ ♪

17:14.951 --> 17:16.953
(shovel digging)

17:42.854 --> 17:44.856
(crying)

17:52.197 --> 17:54.199
♪ ♪

18:16.179 --> 18:18.181
♪ ♪

18:35.114 --> 18:37.075
(slicing)

18:50.880 --> 18:54.092
SAMANTHA:
When Khan died, he became closed off.

18:55.301 --> 18:58.429
He told me that he would
never find the capacity

18:58.513 --> 19:02.892
to love anything again
the way that he loved Khan.

19:02.976 --> 19:04.978
♪ ♪

19:09.983 --> 19:11.985
(growling softly)

19:18.157 --> 19:19.826
(chuckles)

19:19.909 --> 19:21.536
(laughing)

19:21.619 --> 19:23.246
(muttering)

19:23.329 --> 19:26.708
SAMANTHA: Yeah.
He used to write letters all the time.

19:26.791 --> 19:30.378
I don't think I would go a day without,
like, coming back and having, like,

19:30.461 --> 19:33.006
a poem or a letter,
like, waiting on my bed.

19:37.802 --> 19:39.929
(sighs)

19:40.013 --> 19:43.975
I think that Khan's death
kind of killed any happiness

19:44.058 --> 19:48.605
that he had built up
over the two years before that.

19:51.357 --> 19:53.568
He's a totally different person now.

19:58.114 --> 19:59.574
(sniffles)

19:59.657 --> 20:01.576
(crying):
It took me, like...

20:03.244 --> 20:06.331
...a good two hours to get out of bed.

20:17.550 --> 20:20.970
SAMANTHA:
It only kind of slowly occurred to me

20:21.054 --> 20:24.724
that there was, like,
a much deeper darkness.

20:26.601 --> 20:28.937
And that was what worried me the most--

20:29.020 --> 20:32.899
that Harry would react in a way
that would be harmful to himself.

20:39.280 --> 20:42.075
-(chitters)
-(engines buzzing)

20:48.873 --> 20:50.875
(rooster crows)

20:53.670 --> 20:55.755
SAMANTHA:
We just got a message on the sat phone

20:55.838 --> 20:57.674
from a friend in the community of Lucerna.

20:57.757 --> 21:00.259
They're holding a baby ocelot
that they've gotten

21:00.343 --> 21:02.053
from some loggers passing downriver.

21:03.805 --> 21:08.059
This will be the... the first time that
this kind of call has come in since Khan.

21:10.853 --> 21:12.855
(engine rumbling)

21:21.030 --> 21:22.615
Hello.

21:51.728 --> 21:53.730
(purring)

22:03.531 --> 22:06.075
(yowls softly)

22:08.828 --> 22:10.830
(Harry crying)

22:18.880 --> 22:21.049
HARRY:
Thank you. (sniffles)

22:23.718 --> 22:25.261
Thank you.

22:26.804 --> 22:28.222
(device beeping)

22:28.306 --> 22:30.975
(growling)

22:31.059 --> 22:33.227
1.64 pounds.

22:38.399 --> 22:42.320
SAMANTHA: All right, he can get a full
.5 milliliters of both of these, so...

22:42.403 --> 22:43.738
(yowling)

22:43.821 --> 22:45.448
Ooh.

22:49.869 --> 22:51.954
-SAMANTHA (chuckles): Hey.
-(yowling)

22:54.123 --> 22:56.417
(mutters, chuckles)

22:58.419 --> 23:02.882
This little dude is Keanu,

23:02.965 --> 23:05.426
and... (chuckles)

23:05.510 --> 23:08.221
he is our second ocelot rescue.

23:08.304 --> 23:10.973
(yowls)

23:11.057 --> 23:15.561
He will be reintroduced into the wild
in about a year and a half,

23:15.645 --> 23:19.982
and he will be a very aggressive wildcat.

23:23.736 --> 23:26.447
Because of what happened to Khan,

23:26.531 --> 23:29.033
we are planning on moving Keanu.

23:30.451 --> 23:36.082
Moving him to, um, a larger,
safer, more remote area.

23:39.919 --> 23:41.921
♪ ♪

23:51.430 --> 23:53.015
Great.

23:57.311 --> 23:59.188
Tres, dos, uno.

24:00.398 --> 24:01.983
(grunting)

24:02.066 --> 24:04.277
(insects buzzing)

24:04.360 --> 24:06.612
(hammering)

24:08.322 --> 24:10.867
(hammering continues)

24:10.950 --> 24:12.952
(birds chirping)

24:33.139 --> 24:35.266
HARRY:
This is where I'm gonna live from now on.

24:35.349 --> 24:37.351
This is me, this is permanent,

24:37.435 --> 24:43.065
and I'm gonna be here until, um...
until Keanu leaves.

24:43.149 --> 24:45.193
(birds calling)

24:53.284 --> 24:55.203
This is your new home.

24:55.286 --> 24:56.621
Let's see how you like it.

24:57.705 --> 24:59.290
Eh?

25:01.751 --> 25:03.502
Don't give up. Don't give up.

25:03.586 --> 25:04.879
(meows)

